Scolytus aztecus
is an uncommon species and little is known regarding its biology. Scolytus aztecus colonizes both standing trees and felled trees ( Wood 1967 ;
Cibrian Tovar et al. 1995
). The treetops attacked by Scolytus aztecus exhibit red foliage. Scolytus aztecus has been collected feeding in the cambium of large Abies trees, although it has also been collected from Pseudotsuga . Because of limited host records, it is unknown whether the primary host is Abies or Pseudotsuga . Phylogenetic placement of the species suggests Abies (Fig. 4) because the species belongs to a clade of Abies feeding taxa. The adult gallery is transverse across the grain of the wood with a central nuptial chamber, similar in appearance to that of Scolytus ventralis (see
Cibrian Tovar et al. 1995
, fig 132). Larval mines are in the cambium and do not score the wood. Pupation occurs in the cambium ( Wood 1967 ;
Cibrian Tovar et al. 1995
).
